Short answer: ⚠️ Force reboot is NOT the right first solution here.


---

❗ Why force reboot is risky

Your node has:

rook-ceph-osd pod → Cannot evict

👉 That means Ceph is protecting data

If you force reboot:

❌ OSD pod dies abruptly

❌ Data may become degraded

❌ Cluster may go into HEALTH_WARN / HEALTH_ERR

❌ Upgrade may still fail after reboot



---

🔥 When force reboot can work

Force reboot might help ONLY IF:

Node is already drained (not your case ❌)

OR cluster is non-critical/test lab (maybe your case 🤏)



---

🎯 Your situation (based on logs)

👉 Drain is NOT completed

A previously requested drain has not yet completed

👉 So reboot = skipping Kubernetes safety


---

✅ CORRECT APPROACH (Recommended)

Step 1 (SAFE)

Allow eviction:

oc patch pdb rook-ceph-osd -n openshift-storage \
  -p '{"spec":{"minAvailable":0}}'


---

Step 2

Drain again:

oc adm drain ocp-cp-1 \
  --ignore-daemonsets \
  --delete-emptydir-data \
  --force


---

Step 3

Then reboot:

reboot


---

⚠️ If you still want FORCE reboot

👉 Only do this if:

This is LAB environment ✅

You accept temporary storage issues ✅



---

Safe-ish forced reboot sequence:

oc adm cordon ocp-cp-1

Then:

oc debug node/ocp-cp-1
chroot /host
reboot -f


---

🔥 My Recommendation (based on your setup)

Since you are doing disconnected + ODF + upgrade

👉 DO NOT force reboot yet

👉 First fix PDB → then drain → then reboot


---

